ef%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fsalary-raise-controversial-tactic-job-interview-counteroffer-employer-2022-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Eleveraging%20a%20job%20offer%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20a%20competitor%20to%20force%20your%20boss%20to%20give%20you%20a%20raise%2C%20readers%20seem%20to%20divide%20into%20two%20groups.%20On%20one%20side%20are%20the%20bosses%20and%20tenured%20employees%2C%20the%20boomers%20and%20Gen%20Xers.%20%3Cem%3EKids%20these%20days%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20they%20gripe.%20%3Cem%3EDo%20they%20have%20no%20loyalty%3F%3C%2Fem%3E%20On%20the%20other%20side%20are%20the%20younger%20rank-and-file%20employees%2C%20the%20millennials%20and%20Gen%20Zers%2C%20who%20feel%20equally%20aggrieved.%20%3Cem%3EWhy%20should%20I%20be%20loyal%20to%20my%20company%20when%20my%20company%20isn't%20loyal%20to%20me%3F%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20knew%20it%20would%20happen%20again%20the%20other%20month%2C%20when%20I%20was%20reporting%20on%20white-collar%20workers%20who%20secretly%20juggle%20multiple%20full-time%20jobs.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foveremployed-workers-secret-two-multiple-jobs-salaries-tech-tips-2023-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3EOveremployment%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20as%20the%20phenomenon%20is%20known%2C%20violates%20society's%20implicit%20norms%20of%20loyalty%20to%20one's%20employer%20more%20flagrantly%20than%20anything%20else%20I've%20encountered.%20But%20when%20I%20asked%20these%20overemployed%20professionals%20whether%20they%20felt%20bad%20that%20they%20were%20essentially%20cheating%20on%20their%20bosses%2C%20they%20were%20unapologetic.%20%26quot%3BMy%20parents%20told%20me%2C%20'Don't%20switch%20companies%2C%20grow%20in%20one%20company%2C%20be%20loyal%20to%20one%20company%2C%20and%20they'll%20be%20loyal%20to%20you%2C'%26quot%3B%20one%20guy%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BThat%20may%20have%20been%20true%20in%20their%20days%2C%20but%20it%20definitely%20isn't%20today%20anymore.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20the%20story's%20publication%2C%20I%20decided%20to%20dig%20deeper%20into%20the%20concept%20of%20loyalty.%20Where%20did%20this%20norm%20come%20from%3F%20Is%20it%20true%20that%20loyalty%20no%20longer%20pays%3F%20Was%20there%20a%20time%20when%20it%20did%3F%20And%20why%20does%20everybody%20get%20so%20fired%20up%20about%20it%3F%20At%20the%20moment%2C%20there's%20an%20overwhelming%20sense%20that%20work%20%E2%80%94%20and%20the%20underlying%20relationship%20between%20employers%20and%20employees%20%E2%80%94%20is%20fundamentally%20broken.%20Some%20people%20chalk%20it%20up%20to%20the%20discontents%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femployees-defying-orders-return-to-office-great-resistance-remote-work-2022-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Ereturn-to-office%20wars%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%20But%20I%20think%20the%20anger%20runs%20much%20deeper.%20Neither%20employers%20nor%20employees%20feel%20they're%20getting%20what%20they%20expect%20from%20the%20other.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20turns%20out%20there's%20a%20whole%20body%20of%20research%20around%20these%20questions.%20It%20focuses%20on%20what%20organizational%20psychologists%20call%20the%20%3Cem%3Epsychological%20contract%3C%2Fem%3E%20%E2%80%94%20the%20set%20of%20things%20that%20employees%20and%20employers%20believe%20they%20owe%20each%20other%20and%20are%20owed%20in%20return.%20Many%20of%20these%20beliefs%20are%20societal%20in%20scope.%20Others%20emerge%20from%20personal%20experiences%20on%20the%20job.%20But%20for%20the%20psychological%20contract%20to%20hold%20up%2C%20you%20need%20both%20%3Cem%3Emutuality%3C%2Fem%3E%20(both%20parties%20have%20a%20shared%20understanding%20of%20expectations)%20and%20%3Cem%3Ereciprocity%3C%2Fem%3E%20(both%20parties%20believe%20they're%20getting%20a%20fair%20deal).%20Do%20that%2C%20and%20you%20generate%20the%20kind%20of%20trust%20and%20loyalty%20that%20leads%20to%20high%20productivity%20and%20low%20turnover.%20Fail%20to%20do%20that%20and%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0well%2C%20that's%20where%20we%20find%20ourselves%20right%20now.%20A%20world%20in%20which%20the%20psychological%20contract%20is%20profoundly%20broken.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20was%20a%20time%20when%20the%20psychological%20contract%20between%20employers%20and%20employees%20seemed%20unbreakable.%20In%20the%20three%20decades%20following%20World%20War%20II%2C%20as%20Rick%20Wartzman%20documents%20in%20his%20book%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.hachettebookgroup.com%2Ftitles%2Frick-wartzman%2Fthe-end-of-loyalty%2F9781586489151%2F%3Flens%3Dpublicaffairs%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3EThe%20End%20of%20Loyalty%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%26quot%3B%20a%20booming%20economy%20made%20American%20companies%20rich.%20Companies%2C%20in%20turn%2C%20shared%20that%20wealth%20with%20employees%2C%20both%20through%20hefty%20raises%20and%20through%20an%20extraordinary%20expansion%20of%20benefits.%20Companies%20began%20providing%20health%20insurance%2C%20which%20used%20to%20be%20a%20rare%20perk.%20They%20introduced%20profit-sharing%20programs%20and%20pension%20plans.%20They%20offered%20managers%20extensive%20training%2C%20along%20with%20opportunities%20to%20climb%20the%20corporate%20ladder.%20Kodak%2C%20which%20had%20an%2018-hole%20golf%20course%20and%20a%20300%2C000-square-foot%20recreation%20center%20for%20employees%2C%20sponsored%20everything%20from%20picnics%20and%20baseball%20games%20to%20bridge%20and%20badminton.%20%26quot%3BKodak%20justified%20its%20considerable%20spending%20on%20these%20pursuits%2C%26quot%3B%20Wartzman%20writes%2C%20%26quot%3Bas%20good%20for%20employer%20and%20employee%20alike.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20the%20biggest%20perk%20of%20all%20was%20a%20sense%20of%20security.%20Blue-collar%20workers%20faced%20seasonal%20layoffs%2C%20but%20it%20was%20customary%20for%20companies%20to%20recall%20those%20workers%20when%20business%20picked%20up.%20Companies%20like%20Kodak%20went%20even%20further%2C%20delaying%20the%20implementation%20of%20new%20technology%20until%20it%20could%20figure%20out%20how%20to%20retrain%20and%20transfer%20any%20workers%20who%20would%20be%20displaced.%20And%20for%20white-collar%20professionals%2C%20layoffs%20and%20firings%20were%20rare.%20%26quot%3BYou%20might%20not%20advance%20as%20far%20as%20you%20hoped%2C%26quot%3B%20Wartzman%20writes%20of%20managers%20at%20GE%20during%20the%201950s.%20%26quot%3BYou%20might%20be%20shoved%20to%20another%20part%20of%20the%20company%20where%2C%20it%20was%20perceived%2C%20you%20could%20do%20less%20harm.%20But%20you%20had%20to%20mess%20up%20pretty%20badly%20to%20get%20tossed%20out%20completely.%26quot%3B%20Surveys%2C%20Wartzman%20found%2C%20showed%20that%20%26quot%3Bnearly%20100%20percent%26quot%3B%20of%20managers%20thought%20their%20employers%20offered%20good%20job%20security%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0and%20that%20three-quarters%20felt%20%26quot%3Bgood%26quot%3B%20or%20%26quot%3Bvery%20good%26quot%3B%20about%20their%20organizations.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222871%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Men%20in%20ties%20surrounding%20a%20table%20holding%20scientific%20instruments%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65a027c743bb77284b9c53a3%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222181%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EResearchers%20at%20GE%20in%201969.%20Back%20then%2C%20professionals%20enjoyed%20the%20kind%20of%20job%20security%20that%20would%20be%20unthinkable%20today.%20%3Cp%3EFox%20Photos%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20feeling%20persisted%20for%20several%20decades.%20%26quot%3BWhen%20I%20was%20teaching%20in%20the%201970s%20and%20in%20the%20early%201980s%2C%20that%20notion%20of%20job%20security%20as%20a%20fundamental%20feature%20of%20employment%20was%20taken%20for%20granted%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Denise%20Rousseau%2C%20the%20academic%20who%20coined%20the%20concept%20of%20the%20psychological%20contract.%20Today%2C%20disillusioned%20workers%20might%20assume%20that%20the%20norm%20of%20workplace%20loyalty%20was%20nothing%20but%20a%20capitalistic%20ruse%2C%20a%20way%20for%20companies%20to%20exploit%20their%20employees.%20But%20it's%20not%20hard%20to%20see%20why%20so%20many%20workers%20and%20managers%20felt%20a%20genuine%20commitment%20to%20their%20companies%20during%20the%20decades%20of%20American%20prosperity.%20Their%20employers%20were%20good%20to%20them%2C%20so%20it%20made%20sense%20for%20them%20to%20be%20good%20to%20their%20employers.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhat%20changed%20was%20globalization.%20Threatened%20by%20overseas%20competition%2C%20American%20businesses%20began%20exporting%20jobs%20and%20%26quot%3Bdownsizing%26quot%3B%20their%20domestic%20workforces.%20A%20new%20management%20philosophy%20was%20born%20%E2%80%94%20one%20that%20was%20neither%20mutual%20nor%20reciprocal.%20%26quot%3BThey%20don't%20treat%20people%20relationally%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Rousseau%2C%20who's%20a%20professor%20of%20organizational%20behavior%20and%20public%20policy%20at%20Carnegie%20Mellon%20University.%20%26quot%3BThey%20treat%20people%20transactionally%20and%20as%20fungible%2C%20as%20easily%20substituted%20one%20to%20the%20next.%26quot%3B%20One%20by%20one%2C%20long-established%20incentives%20for%20employee%20loyalty%20fell%20by%20the%20wayside.%20Companies%20replaced%20pensions%20with%20401(k)s%2C%20forced%20employees%20to%20shoulder%20a%20greater%20share%20of%20healthcare%20premiums%2C%20scrapped%20supplemental%20health%20insurance%20for%20retirees%2C%20and%20started%20relying%20on%20external%20hires%20rather%20than%20training%20and%20promoting%20from%20within.%20Even%20worse%2C%20during%20the%20Great%20Resignation%2C%20employers%20effectively%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgreat-resignation-pay-gap-new-hires-earning-more-2022-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cu%3Epenalized%20%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cu%3Eemployees%20for%20their%20loyalty%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20offering%20sky-high%20salaries%20to%20attract%20job%20candidates%20while%20neglecting%20their%20existing%20staff.%20As%20I%20reported%20in%202022%2C%20veteran%20employees%20received%20salaries%20that%20were%207%25%20lower%2C%20on%20average%2C%20than%20new%20hires.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EStill%2C%20employees%20were%20slow%20to%20shed%20the%20expectation%20of%20loyalty.%20The%20unspoken%20reality%20is%20that%20many%20of%20us%20still%20feel%20we%20should%20be%20loyal%20to%20our%20bosses.%20Why%20else%20does%20the%20prospect%20of%2C%20say%2C%20shopping%20around%20for%20job%20offers%20feel%20a%20little%20icky%3F%20Even%20if%20we%20know%20that%20layoffs%20happen%20to%20other%20people%2C%20we%20don't%20really%20think%20they'll%20happen%20to%20%3Cem%3Eus%3C%2Fem%3E.%20Instead%2C%20we%20cling%20to%20the%20belief%20that%20there's%20%3Cem%3Ereciprocity%3C%2Fem%3E%20in%20the%20workplace%3Cem%3E%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3Ethat%20we'll%20be%20taken%20care%20of%20as%20long%20as%20we%20do%20what%20our%20employer%20asks%20of%20us.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20person%20who%20believed%20this%20was%20a%20guy%20I'll%20call%20Mark.%20He%20always%20met%20his%20deadlines%20and%20his%20performance%20goals%2C%20and%20his%20clients%20loved%20his%20work.%20But%20in%202016%2C%20his%20company%20laid%20him%20off%20after%20it%20decided%20to%20pursue%20a%20new%20business%20model.%20What%20added%20insult%20to%20injury%20was%20that%20the%20company%20kept%20the%20one%20employee%20Mark%20managed%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0someone%20he%20had%20suggested%20hiring%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0because%20her%20salary%20was%20cheaper.%20His%20boss%20apologized%2C%20telling%20him%20that%20the%20layoffs%20had%20nothing%20to%20do%20with%20him.%20It%20was%20just%20business.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20felt%20betrayed%2C%26quot%3B%20Mark%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BI%20thought%20it%20was%20unfair.%20I%20did%20everything%20I%20was%20expected%20to%20do.%26quot%3B%20But%20then%20he%20had%20an%20epiphany%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0that%20employers%20no%20longer%20shared%20his%20expectation%20of%20loyalty.%20%26quot%3BI%20kind%20of%20grew%20up%20and%20realized%20it's%20just%20how%20things%20are%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%20%26quot%3BYou%20can%20do%20everything%20and%20people%20could%20still%20fire%20you%20for%20no%20reason%20at%20all.%26quot%3B%20Now%2C%20he%20understands%20the%20new%20norm%3A%20%26quot%3BI'm%20always%20expecting%20that%20every%20job%20I%20have%2C%20I%20could%20be%20fired%20tomorrow.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20disillusionment%20is%20what%20academics%20call%20a%20psychological-contract%20violation.%20When%20the%20contract%20holds%2C%20good%20things%20happen.%20But%20when%20it%20breaks%2C%20people%20find%20a%20way%20to%20even%20the%20scales.%20They%20make%20sure%20they're%20not%20putting%20in%20more%20than%20they're%20going%20to%20get.%20They%20resolve%20to%20never%20get%20burned%20again.%20For%20Mark%2C%20this%20meant%20accepting%20freelance%20gigs%20on%20top%20of%20his%20full-time%20job%2C%20and%20then%20taking%20on%20multiple%20full-time%20jobs%20at%20once.%20Today%2C%20he%20juggles%20three%20full-time%20roles%20and%20a%20few%20freelance%20clients.%20When%20it%20comes%20to%20loyalty%2C%20he's%20an%20employer's%20worst%20nightmare%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0because%20he%20has%20none.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOthers%20have%20adapted%20in%20different%20ways.%20Maybe%20they%20refuse%20to%20sacrifice%20their%20nights%20and%20weekends%20to%20meet%20a%20deadline.%20Or%20they%20switch%20jobs%20every%20few%20months%2C%20in%20search%20of%20a%20higher%20paycheck.%20Or%20they%20use%20employee%20training%20programs%20at%20work%20to%20load%20up%20on%20professional%20certifications%2C%20as%20a%20way%20to%20increase%20their%20appeal%20to%20other%20employers.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBy%20not%20being%20loyal%20to%20employees%2C%26quot%3B%20Rousseau%20says%2C%20%26quot%3Borganizations%20have%20failed%20to%20realize%20that%20they're%20not%20going%20to%20get%20loyalty%20in%20return.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EMany%20employers%20have%20responded%20to%20the%20loss%20of%20loyalty%20not%20by%20trying%20to%20repair%20the%20psychological%20contract%2C%20but%20by%20cracking%20down%20on%20anyone%20they%20view%20as%20a%20traitor.%20Some%20have%20enacted%20unofficial%20policies%20to%20never%20hire%20back%20a%20former%20employee.%20Others%20are%20using%20surveillance%20software%20to%20track%20employee%20keystrokes%20in%20an%20effort%20to%20catch%20workers%20who%20are%20coasting%20on%20company%20time.%20Most%20egregiously%2C%20a%20few%20are%20even%20suing%20quitters%20using%20contract%20clauses%20known%2C%20ironically%2C%20as%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2023%2F09%2F27%2Fbusiness%2Ftraining-repayment-agreement-debt.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3ETRAPs%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0training%20repayment%20agreement%20provisions%20that%20require%20workers%20who%20leave%20a%20job%20before%20a%20specified%20date%20to%20reimburse%20their%20employer%20for%20training%20costs.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELast%20year%2C%20I%20reported%20that%20the%20unprecedented%20rise%20in%20remote%20work%20was%20prompting%20employers%20to%20further%20shred%20the%20psychological%20contract%2C%20opting%20to%20hire%20contractors%2C%20temps%2C%20and%20part-timers%20over%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwork-from-home-employers-quiet-quitting-contractors-part-time-gig-2023-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3E%20full-time%20employees%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Work%20from%20home%2C%20in%20fact%2C%20has%20played%20a%20major%20role%20in%20disrupting%20the%20traditional%20bond%20between%20employers%20and%20employees.%20Being%20away%20from%20the%20office%20prompts%20employees%20to%20emotionally%20distance%20themselves%20from%20their%20jobs%20%E2%80%94%20and%20makes%20it%20easier%20for%20employers%20to%20ignore%20their%20needs.%20%26quot%3BI%20do%20hear%20this%20from%20companies%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Nick%20Bloom%2C%20a%20professor%20at%20Stanford%20University%20who's%20an%20expert%20on%20remote%20work.%20%26quot%3BThe%20more%20remote%20someone%20is%2C%20the%20more%20transactional%20it%20feels.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhat%20we%20have%20now%20is%20a%20vicious%20cycle%20of%20broken%20promises%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0companies%20cutting%20back%20on%20benefits%20and%20job%20security%2C%20workers%20cutting%20back%20on%20hours%20and%20effort.%20The%20result%20is%20a%20workplace%20that%20none%20of%20us%20wants%3A%20one%20where%20no%20one%20feels%20they%20owe%20anyone%20anything.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20there%20is%20another%20way.%20%26quot%3BThere's%20a%20pretty%20large%20set%20of%20progressive%20companies%20that%20have%20realized%20the%20old%20times%20aren't%20coming%20back%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Anthony%20Klotz%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20management%20at%20University%20College%20London.%20%26quot%3BThey%20say%3A%20'Whoever%20caused%20it%20doesn't%20really%20matter%20as%20a%20business.%20We%20just%20need%20to%20operate%20effectively.'%20And%20that%20doesn't%20mean%20taking%20the%20non-trusting%20path.%26quot%3B%20As%20in%20any%20relationship%2C%20the%20key%20to%20rebuilding%20trust%20is%20to%20stop%20fighting%20over%20who%20started%20the%20problem%20and%20start%20focusing%20on%20fixing%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20example%3A%20Klotz%20studies%20%26quot%3Balumni%20programs%26quot%3B%20that%20employers%20have%20set%20up%20to%20stay%20in%20touch%20with%20and%20offer%20networking%20opportunities%20to%20former%20staff.%20The%20programs%20aren't%20selfless%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0they%20arise%20out%20of%20a%20recognition%20that%20former%20employees%20sometimes%20turn%20into%20clients%20and%20customers%2C%20a%20situation%20that's%20common%20in%20management%20consulting.%20Former%20employees%20also%20represent%20a%20ready%20talent%20pool%20in%20the%20event%20they%20decide%20to%20come%20back.%20Some%20organizations%20are%20so%20friendly%20to%20their%20quitters%2C%20Klotz%20says%2C%20that%20a%20quarter%20of%20their%20workforce%20consists%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fjob-market-hiring-trends-expect-boomerang-employees-labor-shortage-great-resignation%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Eboomerangs%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Alumni%20programs%20represent%20a%20small%20but%20meaningful%20way%20of%20restoring%20the%20psychological%20contract%20with%20employees.%20Employers%20recognize%20that%20they%20can't%20guarantee%20to%20keep%20employees%20around%20forever%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0but%20they%20can%20tell%20those%20who%20leave%20that%20they're%20always%20welcome%20back.%20It's%20not%20lifetime%20employment%2C%20but%20it%20encourages%20a%20lifelong%20relationship.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI've%20been%20thinking%20about%20other%20ways%20employers%20and%20employees%20could%20renegotiate%20the%20terms%20of%20their%20frayed%20relationship.%20It's%20hard%20to%20imagine%20any%20company%20promising%20total%20job%20security%20these%20days.%20But%20they%20could%20be%20more%20up%20front%20when%20the%20business%20sours%20and%20offer%20voluntary%20buyouts%20before%20they%20resort%20to%20layoffs.%20They%20could%20offer%20meaningful%20opportunities%20for%20learning%20and%20development%2C%20not%20the%20canned%20training%20videos%20that%20no%20one%20watches.%20They%20could%20consider%20internal%20candidates%20for%20new%20openings%20before%20they%20look%20elsewhere%2C%20and%20conduct%20regular%20salary%20reviews%20to%20make%20sure%20they're%20not%20penalizing%20their%20veterans%20for%20sticking%20around.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20return%2C%20employees%20could%20give%20their%20bosses%20a%20new%20kind%20of%20loyalty.%20I'm%20not%20talking%20about%20returning%20to%20the%20old%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhustle-culture-got-america-addicted-to-work%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Ehustle-culture%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20model%20that%20required%20workers%20to%20sacrifice%20everything%20for%20the%20company.%20But%20the%20new%20loyalty%20would%20recognize%20that%20employees%20have%20to%20uphold%20their%20end%20of%20the%20bargain.%20That%20includes%20things%20like%20stepping%20up%20when%20the%20business%20needs%20it%2C%20being%20a%20creative%20and%20productive%20member%20of%20the%20team%2C%20and%20riding%20out%20temporary%20waves%20of%20discontent%20instead%20of%20jumping%20ship%20at%20the%20first%20hint%20of%20trouble.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUltimately%2C%20though%2C%20the%20psychological%20contract%20can't%20be%20reduced%20to%20a%20simple%20ledger%20%E2%80%94%20a%20cool%2C%20calculated%20weighing%20of%20what%20we%20as%20employees%20give%20on%20one%20side%2C%20and%20what%20we%20get%20on%20the%20other.%20%26quot%3BIt's%20not%20tit%20for%20tat%2C%26quot%3B%20Rousseau%20says.%20%26quot%3BIt's%20more%2C%20'the%20way%20you've%20treated%20me%20and%20the%20things%20you've%20asked%20of%20me'%20creates%20beliefs%20about%20how%20we%20should%20relate%20to%20each%20other%20in%20the%20future%2C%20because%20of%20the%20obligations%20we%20feel%20party%20to.%26quot%3B%20In%20other%20words%2C%20mutuality%20and%20reciprocity%20create%20trust%20%E2%80%94%20and%20trust%20generates%20loyalty.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EConsider%20Mark%2C%20the%20guy%20who%20started%20juggling%20three%20full-time%20jobs%20after%20he%20was%20laid%20off.%20Given%20his%20disillusionment%2C%20I%20assumed%20he'd%20give%20each%20of%20his%20employers%20the%20bare%20minimum%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0aiming%20for%20a%20threshold%20of%20%26quot%3Bmeets%20expectations%2C%26quot%3B%20but%20rejecting%20any%20pressure%20to%20go%20above%20and%20beyond.%20Not%20necessarily%20so%2C%20he%20tells%20me.%20It%20depends%2C%20he%20says%2C%20on%20how%20his%20bosses%20at%20each%20of%20his%20companies%20treat%20him.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20somebody%20respects%20me%20as%20a%20person%2C%20if%20they%20show%20me%20that%20they%20value%20the%20work%20that%20I%20do%2C%20if%20they%20show%20me%20that%20the%20work%20that%20I%20do%20has%20impact%2C%20then%20I'm%20going%20to%20go%20the%20extra%20mile%20for%20them%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BI'm%20not%20going%20to%20give%20it%20the%2080%25%20I%20would%20usually%20give%20for%20a%20company%20I'm%20working%20for.%20I'm%20going%20to%20give%20them%2090%20or%20100%25.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20surprised%20me%20that%20someone%20who's%20so%20flagrantly%20breaking%20the%20traditional%20rules%20of%20loyalty%20%E2%80%94%20secretly%20working%20three%20full-time%20jobs!%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0could%20still%20be%20motivated%20to%20give%20it%20his%20all.%20It%20surprised%20me%20even%20more%20that%20the%20salary%20he%20earns%20from%20each%20of%20his%20jobs%20has%20very%20little%20to%20do%20with%20that%20calculus.%20Ultimately%2C%20we're%20social%20creatures%2C%20and%20as%20in%20any%20relationship%20%E2%80%94%20even%20in%20one%20like%20work%2C%20which%20at%20its%20most%20basic%20terms%20is%20an%20exchange%20of%20labor%20for%20money%20%E2%80%94%20the%20most%20disillusioned%20of%20us%20still%20seek%20something%20more%20than%20a%20financial%20transaction.%20We%20want%20to%20be%20seen%20as%20people%2C%20not%20as%20line%20items%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0and%20employers%20can%20take%20the%20first%20step%20to%20repairing%20the%20psychological%20contract%20by%20recognizing%20that%20simple%20truth.%20And%20if%20they%20do%20it%20fully%20and%20faithfully%20enough%2C%20maybe%20we%20can%20begin%20to%20forge%20a%20healthier%20workplace%20dynamic%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0one%20in%20which%20loyalty%2C%20and%20the%20benefits%20that%20accompany%20it%2C%20flows%20both%20ways.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fauthor%2Faki-ito%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EAki%20Ito%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%20is%20a%20chief%20correspondent%20at%20Business%20Insider.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Floyalty-employee-employer-job-security-broken-work-companies-bosses-2024-1%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1705918921000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%